<br>
As far as getting skills up.....<br>
<br>
The only skills that go up slow are defense and dodge.  The rest of the casting skills should max out just by fighting through one bubble of orange.  You absolutely have to get defense and dodge maxed each level or you are screwed hard.  It makes a difference.  Having said that, I see no reason why you couldn't do this and still have a perfectly viable character if you do it correctly.<br>
<br>
Although the time it takes you to cast spells over and over in each of the casting areas to max your skills will probably come closer to the actual time it takes to just level up by fighting.<br>
<br>
If you want to level without fighting you will need a magician and a healer type who are your very good friends because they will get bored.<br>
<br>
Ideally you would do this after each level but theoretically you could wait till you had gained two or three levels.<br>
<br>
In order to get defense and dodge up duel a mage pet, make sure its blue to you and have the mage use earth.  Have your friendly healer standing by to heal you or if no healer just have the mage back his pet off before you die and bind yourself back up to half.<br>
<br>
In order to get your spells skills up pick a low level spell in the area you want to raise and cast it over and over again.  Preferably spells you can cast on yourself.  Clarity helps alot when doing this.  For evocation just nuke yourself with low level spells and bind when you get low or have your healer friend do his thing.<br>
<br>
That is how to do it if you are dead set on doing it that way.  I have done this with a massively power leveled cleric and it worked just fine all his skills were maxed at 40 including defense and dodge... BUT IT WAS BORING AS HELL.<br>
<br>
In my opinion this is a great supplemental source of experience (like when you only have an hour or so to play or just need that last couple of blues to level and can't find a group) but it is way more fun getting levels the old fashioned way.<br>
<br>
